<div id="review_919766065" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/919766065" />
    <a title="Louis Cabri" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1758113-louis-cabri"><img alt="Louis Cabri" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1442477048p2/1758113.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/919766065?book_show_action=true">Apr 24, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Louis Cabri" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Louis Cabri" href="/user/show/1758113-louis-cabri">Louis Cabri</a>
      </span>

          added it


          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9780394502953" href="/book/show/2351039.Platero_and_I">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer919766065" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16533882840835271554">Subtitle of the book is The Elegy. <i>Platero and I</i> consists of 141 narrative prose poems addressed to the poet&apos;s donkey. First published 1914. This Shambhala edition from 1978 is translated by Antonio T. de Nicolas.<br/><br/>Lush, rich images piled one on top of the other. Did Christopher Dewdney read Jimenez? Ron Silliman has characterized Dewdney&apos;s lush imagery as pornographic, I think; if so, then Jimenez&apos;s is the opposite of that. They are both extraordinarily denotative in their use of the image (this </span>
  <span id="freeText16533882840835271554" style="display:none">Subtitle of the book is The Elegy. <i>Platero and I</i> consists of 141 narrative prose poems addressed to the poet's donkey. First published 1914. This Shambhala edition from 1978 is translated by Antonio T. de Nicolas.<br /><br />Lush, rich images piled one on top of the other. Did Christopher Dewdney read Jimenez? Ron Silliman has characterized Dewdney's lush imagery as pornographic, I think; if so, then Jimenez's is the opposite of that. They are both extraordinarily denotative in their use of the image (this appears the case even for Dewdney's Olivia Butleresque scifi <i>Permugenesis</i>, for example), expanding the world by exalting the literal, rather than sealing the world off inside a handful of symbols. Robert "Iron Man" Bly translated Jimenez in the sixties, probably on reconnaissance for his "deep image" (wonder if Bly thought he found any).<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="16533882840835271554" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

